	BankruptcyDaschle Says Bankruptcy Reform Stuck=20
As Party Roles in Conference Still in Limbo

Bankruptcy legislation (S. 420/H.R. 333) that separately passed the Senate=20
and House earlier this spring remains in limbo, as the Senate still cannot=20
agree on how to proceed to conference with the House, Senate Minority Leader=
=20
Thomas Daschle (D-S.D.) told reporters April 23.=20
The question of party representation in conference continues to stall effort=
s=20
to bring the issue of bankruptcy reform to a close. Democrats, who occupy=20
half of the Senate's seats, are insisting upon equal representation in=20
conference, while Republicans oppose it.=20
Efforts to forego a conference with the House are unlikely to succeed given=20
House leadership concerns about a number of controversial amendments the=20
Senate made to S. 420 before passing it. In particular, many Republicans=20
object to provisions opposed by President Bush that are intended to make it=20
harder for debtors to shield assets by purchasing expensive homes in states=20
that bar creditors from seizing the homes in bankruptcy auctions.=20
"There has been no resolution yet," Daschle said. "I would say that I think=20
both [Senate Majority Leader Trent Lott (R-Miss.)] and I and our staffs are=20
working to try to resolve his concern, which is what do you do in a tie ...=20
You know, I think what happens in a tie is [that] you just keep talking unti=
l=20
you break the tie."=20
Daschle said he is looking for an "opportunity to break through," but has ye=
t=20
to find one. Regardless, Daschle said he does not think "tie votes are all=20
that big a problem, either in conference or in committee."=20
With Daschle voting in the affirmative, the Senate March 14 approved 80-19 a=
=20
cloture motion Lott filed late March 12. Sen. Paul Wellstone (D-Minn.), the=20
bill's most outspoken opponent, argued passionately against cloture and Sen.=
=20
Harry Reid (D-Nev.) foiled an attempt by Lott to secure unanimous consent to=
=20
prepare the bill for a conference with House members after the bill passed=20
the Senate March 15.=20
In general, the bills aim to force more bankruptcy filers to file under=20
Chapter 13, which requires some repayment of debts, instead of Chapter 7. Th=
e=20
bills are a copy of last year's conference report worked out between the=20
House and the Senate, which former President Clinton pocket-vetoed in=20
December.=20


